Found it.

The problem is Python 3.14.3.

Not your code.
Not OpenCV.
Not FastAPI.

Python 3.14 is extremely new and many scientific packages still don't have stable wheels for it.

That's why pip is trying to compile NumPy from source:

numpy-2.2.6.tar.gz

instead of downloading a prebuilt wheel.

Then it fails because you don't have:

Visual Studio C++
clang
gcc

installed.

For Check Your Drawings, use:

Python 3.12.x

I would not use:

Python 3.14
Python 3.13

for a computer vision project today.

Clean fix

Delete the current venv:

deactivate

Remove-Item -Recurse -Force .venv

Install Python 3.12.11:

https://www.python.org/downloads/release/python-31211/

During installation:

✓ Add Python to PATH
✓ Install for all users

Verify:

python --version

Expected:

Python 3.12.x

Create venv again:

python -m venv .venv

.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1

python -m pip install --upgrade pip

Then use this simplified requirements.txt:

fastapi
uvicorn[standard]

opencv-python
numpy

Pillow
PyMuPDF

python-multipart

pydantic
pydantic-settings

Install:

pip install -r backend\requirements.txt

You should see wheels downloading instead of source builds.

If you don't want to uninstall Python 3.14, that's fine.

Install Python 3.12 alongside it and create the venv explicitly:

py -3.12 -m venv .venv

Then:

.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1

python --version

should show:

Python 3.12.x

That is the fastest path forward. Once that installs successfully, we'll generate backend/app/config.py next.

